reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on November 3, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Hours of fun!
reviews.reviewText: We have bought these 2 times over the last couple years. Probably some of the best toddler fun you can buy for $20.The styrofoam is very sturdy for the most part - it can be delicate around the tail area. The back piece can be moved to make the plane fly straight and level or do big loops. The four colors are a bonus level of fun. All of our neighborhood kids like to spend hours outside throwing these (ages 3, 5, 6).For younger ages, parents may have to help move the tail piece to avoid tearing the styrofoam, but we’ve only had one instance of that with the 3 year old over the past year.Pros: sturdy, fun, engaging activity that gets the kids out of the house for hoursCon: might tear the tail (low probability) if your 3 year old decides they want to change the tail piece and doesn’t ask for helpEasy 5/5 for this family. I’ll buy them again when we inevitably lose this set!

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on September 18, 2020
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars A great set of gliders ....
reviews.reviewText: Boy, after flying cheap balsa wood gliders, as kids, THESE gliders are great !! Bought these for a family member, who loves aviation. These seem to be pretty durable, as we've flown/crashed them plenty of times, and they hold up well. Be careful when assembling them, as they are still only made out of some sort of rubberized foam. If you grip them wrong, and force them too much during installation, it might be easy to snap a tail piece, etc.. But the average person, using a small amount of CARE, will not have any problem.They fly well. Experiment, as far as WHERE you hold it, while throwing, and the direction you throw. Throwing into a 'slight' breeze, seems to work really nice. We've even played around with taping a small weight (think penny, nickel, or dimes) to certain parts of the gliders, to see if it will help or hurt the flight of the glider. It's been a fun learning tool. I was uncertain how these gliders would HOLD UP, after they crashed a few times. Back as kids, those gliders didn't hold up very long. Well, these new gliders hold up very well (at least from this company, as lots of vendors sell similar ones). We've put in 2 - 3 sessions, of +30 minutes, out in a paved dead-end street. No issues. I was pleasantly surprised. We started out by buying a smaller version of this, and liked it so well, that we upgraded to these larger models (and they include TWO gliders, for the price). Try them, your kids should love them. And if they don't abuse them, they should last for quite a while.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on March 4, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 4.0 out of 5 stars Very durable, weight 27-35g
reviews.reviewText: I bought these to toss in the back yard with the toddler. I bought a 4-pack thinking they wouldn’t last very long - but I was wrong. These things are not like the foam gliders we bought in the 90’s. They can take a huge beating! I have hit the concrete, furniture, trees, etc and while the nose crumpled a bit - it still flys fine.The thing to note is that I found one plane flew rather poorly - diving to the ground within a few feet while rolling to the right. This was somewhat fixable by warping the wings and tail to correct the flight path.One plane flew particularly well and here is why. Of the 4 planes, the one that flew badly has a weight of 35.5g. The one that flew great has a weight of 27.5g. The nose weight part of the heavy pane weighs 2g more than the nose weight of the light plane - which helps explain its tendency to nosedive.So if you get one that drops down, maybe remove the canopy (carefully, it is attached with what looks like a dab of hot glue) and remove from carefully remove a gram or 2 of foam from the inside - then put it back on. The steel ball weighs 5.5 grams so maybe replacing that with 3.5-4g of something will improve its flight.

reviews.reviewText: Got these for the kids at a summer get together. Easy to put together, and they seemed fairly sturdy, but there's nothing really special about the flying--basically they do a loop de loop and glide a little. Still, the kids got a big kick out of throwing them around, and several hours they were all still intact.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on November 6, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Tons of fun
reviews.reviewText: I gave these to four of my grandchildren to play with at a family event (to keep them entertained). They were a hit, and as soon as I broke them out, these planes got no rest. And when they figured out that there were two ways to fly them, they were intrigued. The planes are not super sturdy, and a couple of them had dings on the nose after all the playing, but it didn't affect their flying. Lots of fun!
These planes work well and kids love them. They do break easily.
